Headlines.Author: Michael Calia
Headlines.Headline: Cintas, Shred-it Agree to Combine Shredding Operations

PARAGRAPH.#text: Cintas Corp. CTAS and Shred-it International Inc. have agreed to combine their document-shredding operations. Business-service provider Cintas said it would own 42% of the combined operation, and expects to receive $180 million in cash when the transaction closes. Shred-it shareholders will own the remaining 58% of the company. The new company will be led by current Shred-it Chief Executive Vince DePalma. Karen Carnahan, the operating chief of Cintas' document-management division, will become chief operating officer of the new company.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: Cintas, Shred-it Agree to Combine Shredding Operations

PARAGRAPH.#text: DOW JONES NEWSWIRES Standard & Poor's Ratings Services lowered Cintas Corp.'s CTAS corporate credit rating one notch, citing the company's aggressive financial policy and weaker credit ratios. The ratings agency cut Cintas to BBB+, three steps above junk status, from A-. The outlook is stable. "The downgrade reflects the company's more aggressive financial policy including potential debt-financed share repurchase activity and weaker pro forma credit ratios that are consistent with 'BBB' rating category medians," said Standard & Poor's credit analyst Jerry Phelan.

PARAGRAPH.#text: By Kristina Peterson Bullish sentiment was enough to help U.S. stocks overcome news of a big drop in new-home sales last month to finish in the black for a fourth session in a row Wednesday, though thin pre-holiday trading volumes restricted the advance. PARAGRAPH.#text: Stock investiors in coming week will weigh more data showng growing recovery against inevitability that low Fed interest rates will dissipate as economy strengthens.

Headlines.Author: Laura Mandaro
Headlines.Headline: MARKET SNAPSHOT: Better Economic Times Vie With Rate Hike Prospects

PARAGRAPH.#text: By Laura Mandaro U.S. stock investors in the week ahead will grapple with an increasingly familiar theme -- that better economic data may ring a death knell for the era of the ultralow rates that helped markets rebound this year. The S&P 500 (SPX) and the Dow Jones Industrial Average (DJI) ended lower in the past week, unable to shrug off rate shivers after Federal Reserve detailed an end to some of its special liquidity programs. These have effectively lowered rates on many consumer loans. The Fed also improved its outlook on the economy.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: MARKET SNAPSHOT: Better Economic Times Vie With Rate Hike Prospects

, a photonics firm, warned that sales for the third-quarter would be about $41 million, with earnings of 2 cents to 3 cents a share. Headlines.Author: Frank Barnako
Headlines.Headline: Schwab to emphasize Internet

#text:
Charles
    Schwab & Co. Inc.

will offer Internet access and seminars about investing online
    at its 270 branch offices next year. Gideon Sasson, Enterprise President of
    Electronic Brokerage said Schwab sees the Internet as a vital tool for investors.
    "Online investing is evolving. Phase one was about early adopters getting on the
    Internet and a fragmented marketplace of firms fighting a price war at the cost of
    providing service, quality information and quick access. Phase two is about providing
    millions more investors with access to an Internet experience where investing smart at a
    good value is paramount. Phase two is here." Schwab says it has 1.1 million active
    online accounts and over $77 billion in online customer assets. The firm added nearly
    500,000 new active online accounts in the first 10 months of 1997, which it says is more
    than the entire customer base of the next nearest online competitor.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: Schwab to emphasize Internet

Headlines.Author: CBS.MarketWatch.com
Headlines.Headline: Tel-Save sets market test on AOL

#text:
Tel-Save
    Holdings, Inc.

announced that Thursday it will launch a full scale, online marketing
    test of its long distance service offering to the entire America
    Online

customer base. The national test to all AOL members is the final phase before
    Tel-Save and AOL launch a full-scale advertising and promotional campaign in mid-January.
    Results of the online test will be announced Friday, the company said. Tel-Save paid AOL
    $100 million to be the online service's long-distance service merchant. In a recent
    federal securities filing, Tel-save said between two and six percent AOL's customers will
    need to sign up for its long distance service in order for Tel-Save to break even on its
    investment. Tel-Save Chairman and CEO Daniel Borislow said his company will offer
    AOL subscribers a long distance service costing nine cents a minute. "We've harnessed
    the power of the internet and electronic commerce through AOL to deliver huge savings and
    convenience to consumers," he said.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: Tel-Save sets market test on AOL

Headlines.Headline: Software Report

#text: Broderbund

shares edged lower Thursday even though the maker of entertainment and productivity
    software handily topped analysts' earnings estimates. The company said after the market
    closed yesterday that it earned 49 cents per share, 4 cents ahead of the consensus
    estimate. Revenue surged 61 percent to $99 million, about $10 million higher than the
    Street expected. David Farina, analyst at William Blair, said strong shipments of the Riven game -- the sequel to the best-selling software game of all-time, Myst
    -- led growth. Sales of education titles were soft, while productivity software rose about
    29 percent, Farina said. He added he had no idea why the stock declined; after initially
    rising, shares dropped 2 1/4 to 31 1/2 in early trading.
